---
import BaseLayout from "@layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import Button from "@components/Button.astro";
import Card from "@components/Card.astro";
const title = 'Independent SAP BTP Architect — Boundary Model';
const description = 'Builder-side authority on SAP BTP architecture. Boundary Model, structural diagnosis, and contract-bound verdicts. Not implementation services.';
---
<BaseLayout {title} {description}>
  <!-- Hero -->
  <section class="stack hero">
    <h1 style="margin-bottom:.25rem;">Independent SAP BTP Architect</h1>
    <p class="lede">Builder‑side authority on post‑go‑live SAP BTP extensions when architecture is still being worked on but no longer being decided. I issue contract‑bound architectural verdicts — what must change, what must remain, and who holds jurisdiction. Some SAP BTP issues continue to be worked on long after they have stopped being decidable internally.</p>
    <div style="display:flex; gap:.75rem; flex-wrap:wrap; margin-top: 1rem;">
      <Button href="/boundary-model/" variant="ghost">Read the Boundary Model</Button>
      <Button href="/work/" variant="primary">Engagement formats</Button>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="measure perspective" style="margin: var(--space-6) 0;">
    <div class="eyebrow">Perspective</div>
    <p>Former platform engineer at SAP; worked across multitenancy, identity propagation, integration boundaries, and lifecycle orchestration on SAP BTP.</p>
    <p>The Boundary Model emerged from repeated post–go-live failures observed from inside the platform layer.</p>
  </div>

  

  <!-- Who this is for -->
  <section class="stack">
    <h2>Who this is for</h2>
    <p class="measure">This site is for architects, technical leads, and decision‑makers facing post–go‑live instability in SAP BTP extensions.</p>
    <p class="measure"><strong>Typical pattern:</strong><br />
      Documentation appears correct.<br />
      Ownership is unclear.<br />
      Behavior differs by tenant, entry path, or identity context.<br />
      The system is “technically correct” — yet fails in practice.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- What I actually do / do not do -->
  <section class="feature">
    <Card eyebrow="Scope" title="What I actually do">
      <ul>
        <li>Diagnose <strong>boundary failures</strong> across runtime context, identity propagation, tenant isolation, data ownership, integration jurisdiction, and lifecycle authority.</li>
        <li>Issue a <strong>written verdict</strong>: what must change vs what must not change.</li>
        <li>Re‑establish <strong>jurisdiction</strong>: who owns what, and where.</li>
      </ul>
    </Card>
    <Card eyebrow="Not offered" title="What these engagements are not">
      <ul>
        <li>These engagements do not replace implementation teams.</li>
        <li>They are not designed for ticket execution or staff augmentation.</li>
        <li>They are not generic consulting support.</li>
      </ul>
    </Card>
  </section>

  

  <!-- Decision signals -->
  <section class="stack">
    <h2>You may need an independent verdict when…</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>The system runs, but no team can legitimately approve the next change.</li>
      <li>Different teams can explain the problem, but no team can end the decision.</li>
      <li>Rollout, tenant onboarding, or security hardening reveals that the original architecture was never governable.</li>
      <li>It works in Postman but fails behind App Router or Work Zone.</li>
      <li>Local fixes continue, but ambiguity does not decrease.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <!-- Distinction section -->
  <section class="stack">
    <h2>When this is no longer an implementation problem</h2>
    <p class="measure">Troubleshooting improves parts of a path. Architectural verdicts restore legitimacy across boundaries. If multiple teams are locally correct but the architecture remains globally unstable, the problem has crossed from implementation into decision failure.</p>
    <p class="measure">At this point the question is jurisdiction — identity, tenant, data ownership, integration contracts, lifecycle gates — not more effort. The decision must define what changes and who can approve it.</p>
    <p><a href="/implementation-vs-verdict/">Implementation vs verdict →</a> · <a href="/internal-alignment-failed/">When internal alignment has failed →</a></p>
  </section>

  

  <!-- Entry paths -->
  <section class="feature">
    <div>
      <h2>Choose your path</h2>
      <p class="measure">Three fast ways to make this legible and bounded.</p>
      <div style="display:flex; gap:.75rem; flex-wrap:wrap;">
        <Button href="/boundary-model/" variant="ghost">Understand the model</Button>
        <Button href="/failure-patterns/" variant="ghost">Recognize the pattern</Button>
        <Button href="/what-an-independent-verdict-does/" variant="primary">Understand the decision action</Button>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="stack">
      <Card eyebrow="Foundation" title="Boundary Model">
        <p class="measure">Canonical definition of six boundaries and why traditional reviews miss these failures.</p>
        <a href="/boundary-model/">Read the model →</a>
      </Card>
      <Card eyebrow="Patterns" title="Failure Patterns">
        <p class="measure">Recurring symptoms of boundary and jurisdiction failure in SAP BTP extensions.</p>
        <a href="/failure-patterns/">See patterns →</a>
      </Card>
      <Card eyebrow="Decision" title="What an independent verdict does">
        <p class="measure">Inputs, assessment, outputs, and boundaries — without implementation takeover.</p>
        <a href="/what-an-independent-verdict-does/">Make it legible →</a>
      </Card>
    </div>
  </section>

  

  <!-- Work with me -->
  <section class="stack cta">
    <h2>Work with me</h2>
    <p class="measure">Contract‑bound architectural judgment. Fixed‑scope verdicts — not implementation. See formats and expectations.</p>
    <Button href="/work/" variant="primary">Engagement formats</Button>
  </section>

  

  <!-- Closing CTA -->
  <section class="stack">
    <h2>When to call me</h2>
    <p class="measure">If an independent architectural decision is required, send a concise one‑page summary. You will receive a structured assessment — not a sales process.</p>
    <div style="display:flex; gap:.75rem; flex-wrap:wrap;">
      <Button href="/when-to-call-me/" variant="ghost">Signals and next steps</Button>
      <Button href="/contact/" variant="primary">Send a 1‑page summary</Button>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
